segments.text: Ruth, were you or your sisters ever sick out of the mines?
Were any of the other families?
So the doctor didn't come out there very often?
No, he come to the houses.
And did you have to pay for that visit or did Mr. Goodman?
He has to pay every one.
Do you remember how much he had to pay?
About three dollars every time he came to the house.
Do you remember the name of that doctor?
You said that you met your husband when you were
And then you got married, and then you moved here to Rockdale?
And then what did you do together, you and your husband?
Well, I still work in an arrest home, and my husband, he have a nice job.
And I built a new house, me and my husband.
You and your husband built this house?
Did friends come over and help you at all?
And you didn't have Raymond and Junior to help you?
Raymond, he helped a little bit, yes.
Where did your husband pick up the ability to build a house?
Because he worked in the railroad.
Yes, sir, and he gave us this.
Did your husband come from Mexico?
And he finished the school in Waco.
You said you did not go to school at all.
Because my mother, she didn't have the money to send me to school.
Sometimes I cried because I asked her for other reasons.
She didn't want me to go to school.
She said, daughter, I don't have the money for you to go to school.
So the miners, the mining people had to pay the school to send their children to school.
Were some of the miners children's?
Do you remember where that school was?
Well, how did you learn your English?
I mean, you talk very good English.
Well, I started to miss a lot of friends, and I started to learn.
You picked it up from the children who were going to school?
Your father, Joe Mendoza, was from Mexico.
He was from Mexico, and he was a boss man at mines.
Did he... You know, I asked you this before, if he...
kept up some of the old ways from Mexico?
What kind of things did he do?
Did he retain the same religion, for instance?
He never changed anything from Mexico?
Was he a Catholic in Mexico?
Do you remember any of the other miners that changed from Catholicism to another church?
Because we've gotten reports that some of them became Baptists, but everybody at the Boniva mine remained.
Did you have a church at the mining camp?
And you held church at the mining camp?
What would happen when it was raining or cold?
Did you just not have church?
One thing I forgot when we were talking about feeding, what kind of food that you had, were you able to get a supply of milk at all?
Did Mr. Panera have cows there?
Do you remember how much he told you?
Did you ever hear your father, Joe Mendoza, complain about working in the mines?
What was his attitude toward Mr. Benever?
Did he get along with Mr. Benever?
Did you get married in Rockvale?
Do you remember any weddings out at the mine camps?
You know, other people getting married there?
Let me just sort of wrap this up.
I pretty much asked you everything I wanted to.
How do you remember the mines?
You say that sometimes you sit back and just think about the mines when you take Raymond or Junior to town.
And you're buying them clothes and stuff.
And it's a much different lifestyle, better lifestyle than what you had.
What do you think about the mines along those lines?
Yes, that's why the reason I remember.
Because I don't have what he had.
What kind of feeling does it give you?
You feel pretty bad about it?
But I guess you feel good that you and your husband have been able to... Oh, yes, because my family, he has what I don't have.
You know the way I make the bowls to play me and my brothers and my sister?
Oh, you made little bowls to play with?
You know the way I make it?
No, how did you do that?
I steal some rags to my mother.
And I started to make it, me and my brothers and my sister.
And I steal some sacks to my mother.
And look at this one, he has two or three paws over there.
Yes, that she bought at the store.
Now, you wanted to tell me how you made cornbread, and you wanted to do it in Spanish because you felt like you could explain it better.
So this is how you and your mother made cornbread out of limes, right?
I'll be able to understand some of it now.
Go through the process of how you made the cornmeal.
Was cornmeal fairly... Did you eat cornmeal a lot?
So did your mother taught you how to make the cornmeal?
He told me the way he cooked, but I never learned.
But you know the description of it.
Tell us how your mother made the cornmeal.
Well, I'm going to start it in my own language.
She cooked it, she ground it in the mortar.
And she made tortillas for the family.
And she washed it in the mill before.
She did her chores in the house.
Y este, todo el da ella se preocupaba por su familia.
Y planchaba con planchas de mano.
Y un ratito que tena ella de descanso, se pona a tejer, a hacernos ropa.
Y arreglar la ropa para mi pap, mis hermanos.
Ella trabaja mucho en estos lugares.
Le cocinaba al seor Guniver, le haca tamales, enchiladas, cuando l peda.
Y de esa manera pasaba nuestra vida nosotros.
Yeah, I got some of that.
My daddy, he started to make dances in the houses and he come a lot of people and have a good time.
And the dances, he stop about one o'clock and everybody go home.
So people would come from Rockdale to the dances?
Was that usually on the weekends?
And, well, everybody had a good time.
I think, do you remember hearing a story about a Model T falling down one of the mine shafts?
I remember that real good, but my daddy, he talking about that.
What did he say about it?
Was there ever any contact between the Boniva camp and the other camps?
Did you know people that worked at the other mines?
One thing I noticed when we were walking over the mines last week was that at the Boniva mine, the railroads seemed to be fairly far away from where the miners lived.
Did the railroads keep you up at night?
Because at some of the other mines, the camps were closer to the railroads.
Did you ever see Mr. Ginniver yourself, or did you just hear about him?
I have years and years I never see him.
Somebody else told me he saw him in San Antonio.
And I never tried to go there and see him.
I don't know if he still lives or not.
Well, I think he's passed away.
You said that you had a table and two chairs, and yet you had your mother, your father, and your sisters.
When you ate, did your mother and father sit in the chairs and you sit on the beds?
Did you have any chores that your mother had you doing during the day?
Did you have to weed the garden or anything?
Did anybody ever come through the camp selling watermelons?
Some people would come over there.
Were you all ever able to buy that?
Did any of your friends at the mines meet their husbands or wives at the mines and get married?
There were different families living at the mine.
Was a daughter from one family ever marry a son from another?
Yes, there's a lot of families.
And yet, you went all the way to Waco to meet your husband.
That's kind of unusual, I guess.
Do you keep in contact with any people that you grew up with at Des Moines?
He live in Rockdale, Miss Mireles.
Did they all live in Rockdale?
Where did, not everybody from the mine stayed in the Rockdale area when they shut down, did they?
Well, I can't think of anything else.
I mean, we've covered all the food and the clothes and everything like that.
